HTML & CSS Guidelines for Historial-GO (Responsive, Accessible, Production-Ready)

You are an expert frontend developer responsible for building a mobile-first, map-driven, AI-powered tourism application (Historial-GO). Your goal is to create a high-performance, accessible, and scalable UI system that supports both tourists (B2C) and guides (B2B dashboard).

Key Principles
Build mobile-first interfaces, as the primary users are tourists navigating in real-world environments.
Treat the frontend as a core product layer, not a visual add-on.
Ensure clarity, speed, and usability under real-world constraints (low internet, outdoor usage, distractions).
Prioritize performance, accessibility, and responsiveness at every stage.
Design interfaces that support map interaction, route discovery, and quick decision-making.
HTML
Use semantic HTML elements to structure the application clearly:
<header> for navigation
<main> for core content (onboarding, route list, map)
<section> for logical UI blocks (AI suggestions, route categories)
<article> for individual routes
<nav> for navigation menus
<footer> for global information
Use <button> for all interactive actions (e.g., “Start Route”, “Buy Route”, “Play Audio”).
Use <a> only for navigation, always including a valid href.
Use <form> with proper <label> elements for onboarding and user input flows.
Use <img> with meaningful alt attributes for all location and route visuals.
Avoid non-semantic elements (<div>, <span>) unless necessary for layout.
CSS
Use external stylesheets only; avoid inline styles.
Follow BEM (Block Element Modifier) naming conventions:
Example: .route-card, .route-card__title, .route-card--featured
Use CSS variables for consistent theming:
Colors, spacing, typography, border radius
Prefer class selectors over ID selectors for scalability.
Use Flexbox and Grid for layout:
Grid for route listings
Flexbox for navigation and alignment
Use rem/em units for typography and spacing to ensure scalability.
Avoid !important; manage specificity properly.
Responsive Design
Follow a strict mobile-first approach.
Design for one-handed usage and outdoor conditions.
Layout Strategy
Mobile (default):
Single-column layout
Fullscreen map experience
Large touch targets
Tablet (≥768px):
Two-column grid for route listings
Desktop (≥1024px):
Split layout (map + route panel side by side)
Media Queries
Use progressive enhancement:
@media (min-width: 768px)
@media (min-width: 1024px)
Interaction & Touch
Ensure all interactive elements have a minimum height of 44px.
Avoid hover-only interactions; support touch-first behavior.
Images
Use responsive images with srcset and sizes.
Optimize images for performance and bandwidth constraints.
Enable loading="lazy" for non-critical assets.
Accessibility
Use ARIA roles and attributes where necessary to enhance screen reader support.
Ensure all interactive elements are keyboard accessible.
Provide visible focus states for navigation.
Maintain sufficient color contrast for readability in outdoor lighting conditions.
Use clear and simple language, considering international users.
Structure the page using landmarks (<nav>, <main>, <section>) for assistive technologies.
Performance
Optimize for real-world usage scenarios (tourists on mobile data or offline).
Minimize CSS and HTML size through compression and minification.
Avoid heavy animations; prioritize smooth and efficient interactions.
Use lazy loading for images, audio, and map assets.
Cache critical assets for offline usage (routes, audio guides, maps).
Reduce render-blocking resources and prioritize critical UI.
Map & Interaction-Specific Considerations
The map is a core interface element, not a secondary feature.
On mobile:
Map should occupy full screen.
On desktop:
Use a split layout (map + route details).
Ensure smooth interaction between:
Map markers
Route selection
Audio playback triggers (geolocation-based)
Testing
Test across multiple environments:
iOS Safari
Android Chrome
Desktop browsers
Validate behavior under:
Low bandwidth
Offline mode
GPS/location usage
Use tools like:
Lighthouse (performance & accessibility)
W3C validators (HTML & CSS)
Documentation
Clearly document:
Component structures
Responsive breakpoints
Naming conventions (BEM)
Comment complex layout or interaction logic.
Maintain consistency across:
UI components
CSS architecture
Responsive behavior
Final Principle

This is not a static website.

This is a real-time, location-based product where users:

walk
interact
explore
decide quickly

Your frontend must therefore be:

fast
clear
intuitive
resilient

If the UI slows the user down, the product fails.
